We carried out de-novo signature extraction using sigprofiler. Two analyses were run, one where large samples were down-sampled and one where all the data was used. In both cases similar proportions were observed:

Calculate cosine similarities of the decomposition for the two different panels

M=dim(countsc)[2]
csmlots=sapply(1:M,function(x) cos_sim(countsc[,x],t2$reconstructed[,x]))
csmfewer=sapply(1:M,function(x) cos_sim(countsc[,x],t3$reconstructed[,x]))
csm=data.frame(name=colnames(countsc),csmlots=csmlots,csmfewer=csmfewer,diff=csmlots-csmfewer)
print(csm)

The following illustrates how replacing SBS5, SBS9 and SBS40 by just SBS5 and SBS19, SBS23 by SB19 has very little effect on the other inferred signature contributions - compare the 2nd and 3rd of the following plots where the 2nd is simply an aggregation of the fitted signatures shown in the first plot whereas the 3rd plot shows the contributions when just the reduced signature set is fitted:

par(mfcol=c(3,1))
do_stacked_plot(PDD,t2$contribution,"Signature Contributions: Full Signature Set: Refitted")
do_stacked_plot(PDD,contragg,"Signature Contributions: Aggregated Refitted Signatures")
do_stacked_plot(PDD,t3$contribution,"Signature Contributions: Reduced Signature Set: Refitted")

So the relative contributions of SB5,SB9 and SBS40 are unstable and so we going forward we represent these flat signatures by signature 5 which is known to be a pervasive clock-like signature.

Trees

This shows the branch composition of the various clades on a per patient basis

par(mfcol=c(6,2))
cols=c("grey","red","lightblue","blue","darkblue","pink")
for(PD in PDD){
N=dim(PD$nodes)[1]
tmp=markup_tree(PD$pdx$tree_ml,PD$nodes$node[PD$nodes$status>=0])
PD$pdx$tree_ml$color=cols[tmp$type+1]
tree=plot_basic_tree(PD$pdx,label = PD$patient,style = "classic",cex.label=0,lwd=2,legpos = NULL)
legend("topleft",c("Wild Type",PD$nodes$driver3[PD$nodes$status>=0]),col=cols[1:(N+1)],lwd=2)
}

The following contain also use Chi-square to test if JAK2 C>T @ CpG differs from WT but this time display the aggregated JAK2 counts

res=do_ctccpg_plot_pooled(PDD,countsc,b.jak2.v.wt = TRUE,b.show.p = FALSE)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'patient'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

The counts are as follows:

res=res[,1:4] %>% group_by(patient) %>% 
    filter(status!="Other") %>% mutate(ct_at_cpg=ctsums,not_ct_at_cpg=csums-ctsums) %>% 
    dplyr::select(-c("csums","ctsums")) %>% 
    pivot_wider(names_from = "status",values_from=c("ct_at_cpg","not_ct_at_cpg")) %>% 
    mutate(p.value=chisq.test(matrix(c(ct_at_cpg_WT, not_ct_at_cpg_WT, ct_at_cpg_JAK2,not_ct_at_cpg_JAK2),byrow=TRUE,ncol=2))$p.value) %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    mutate(p.value.bonf=p.adjust(p.value,method = "bonferroni"))
kable(res,"html") %>% kable_styling("striped")
